00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:52.270 position:61%
So let's look at this set of rules that
we've created for producing questions.

00:06:52.270 --> 00:06:54.520
There are 4 rules here.

00:06:54.520 --> 00:07:00.310 position:59%
I want you to know that it took us
about 8 years to create those 4 rules.

00:07:00.310 --> 00:07:04.970 position:73%
Now, I'm sure you're all doing the math there
and figuring that we've done 1/2 a rule a year.

00:07:04.970 --> 00:07:11.320 position:73%
Actually, what we had to do is we had to figure
out how not to create a list of a hundred rules

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:14.920
on how to get students who were
not accustomed to asking questions

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:16.550 position:59%
to actually start producing questions.

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:20.130
And we tried to look at what's
the simplest way to do that.

00:07:20.130 --> 00:07:21.740
And here are the 4 rules.

00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:24.460 position:67%
Number 1, ask as many questions as you can.

00:07:24.460 --> 00:07:27.920 position:72%
Two, do not stop to answer, judge, or discuss.

00:07:27.920 --> 00:07:31.790
Three, write down every question
exactly as stated.

00:07:31.790 --> 00:07:34.790 position:69%
And 4, change any statements into questions.

00:07:34.790 --> 00:07:38.900 position:59%
Of course, we would like the first
one, ask as many questions as you can,

00:07:38.900 --> 00:07:42.130 position:69%
to be sufficient, but as you know, it's not.

00:07:42.130 --> 00:07:46.690 position:56%
There's a need to create a structure
and a safe space for doing that.

00:07:46.690 --> 00:07:50.090 position:66%
So take a moment, look at those questions,
and think about what might be difficult

00:07:50.090 --> 00:07:54.280
for you in following these rules.

00:07:57.180 --> 00:08:01.440 position:58%
